                            <comment id="101075" author="olivergierke" created="Fri, 28 Mar 2014 02:19:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;You should be able to simply implement a &lt;tt&gt;Converter&amp;lt;YourEnum, String&amp;gt;&lt;/tt&gt; and an &lt;tt&gt;Converter&amp;lt;String, YourEnum&amp;gt;&lt;/tt&gt; to customize the serialization of your enums. See the &lt;a href=&quot;http://docs.spring.io/spring-data/mongodb/docs/current/reference/html/mapping-chapter.html#mapping-explicit-converters&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;reference documentation&lt;/a&gt; for details.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="101209" author="w_c_smith" created="Mon, 31 Mar 2014 22:49:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m aware that I can do that. The suggestion is to eliminate the requirement for implementing a pair of converters for any enum type by having a generic handling for an enum &quot;replacement-value field&quot; as Jackson implements: using &lt;tt&gt;@JsonValue&lt;/tt&gt; on an enum class&apos;s field automatically invokes two-way conversion without any additional code.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="101238" author="thomasd" created="Tue, 1 Apr 2014 05:17:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hello Christopher,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;regarding the &quot;@JsonValue&quot;-like feature have you had a look at: &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/DATAMONGO-886&quot; title=&quot;Add @DbObjectValue to define custom DBObject representations of domain objects.&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;DATAMONGO-886&quot;&gt;DATAMONGO-886&lt;/a&gt;?&lt;br/&gt;
I think this pretty much covers what you are asking for  &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers,&lt;br/&gt;
Thomas&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="105396" author="w_c_smith" created="Mon, 7 Jul 2014 09:10:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I managed to miss that last comment. Yes, these appear to be duplicate requests.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
